rt graph rendering, so I need to actually implement that. My plan is to use topological sorting to assign layers, arrange steps horizontally within each layer, and draw colored wires between them with result labels—merging wires that share destinations where possible.\n\nNow I'm working through the actual rendering algorithm: assigning layers via longest-path depth, positioning columns within each layer, and routing wires between rows... Building the diagram...\n\nI'm realizing the current approach is getting too complicated with arbitrary positioning. A simpler vertical layout where each step appears as a row with colored wires connecting outcomes to their destinations would be much cleaner and easier to implement. I'm reconsidering whether a simpler box-and-arrow format actually captures what \"ASCII-art graph\" means, or if the user expects something more visually sophisticated. The merged-wire approach seems reasonable for simplifying the diagram, but I should think through what the final visualization will actually look like.\n\nLet me try rendering this as a proper layered graph with vertical flow...\n\nBuilding the graph structure... I'm realizing the ASCII art approach is too constraining for complex workflows, so I'll switch to a step-centric layout where each box represents a step and its outgoing connections are listed below with color-coded arrows. For the list mode without arguments, I'll show container and host workflows separately. Now I need to structure the implementation with a main command handler, workflow discovery logic, list mode rendering, and the workflow visualization function.\n\nFor the graph rendering, I'll iterate through steps in topological order, draw each as a box, and display outgoing wires grouped by destination with merged connections. Terminal nodes like done and abort get special formatting. I'm mapping out an ANSI color scheme where success paths are green, failures are red, and other result types use blue, yellow, magenta, and cyan for visual distinction.\n\nNow I need to decide whether to detect TTY support for color output or just always include colors—I'll check how the health command handles this in the existing codebase.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2312,"cache_read_input_tokens":39154,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2312},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"824f09ed-450b-4e33-88c5-1585f66e5eba","uuid":"c6f8c62b-2f79-496e-a955-bedfa5094933"}
