{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01RWa2YpTJKr4S8BdkCDL4zA","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a thorough understanding of the codebase. Let me also check the ParseForContainer function and how it works, since I'll need to load both container and host workflows.\n\nNow let me implement the feature. I'll create:\n\n1. `cmd/cloche/workflow.go` - Main implementation\n2. `cmd/cloche/workflow_test.go` - Tests\n3. Updates to `cmd/cloche/main.go` and `cmd/cloche/help.go`\n\nFor the ASCII art graph, I'll use a step-centric vertical layout:\n- Each step is rendered as a box\n- Below each box, outgoing wires are shown as branches\n\n\n- Same-destination wires are merged and colored based on result names\n- Terminal nodes like done and abort get distinctive styling\n\nRather than trying to implement a fully general 2D graph layout, which would be extremely complex, I'll focus on a clean, readable representation that clearly shows the workflow structure.\n\nMy plan is to order steps topologically, draw each as a labeled box, and show outgoing connections as colored branches below each step, with the entry point and terminal nodes clearly marked. This mirrors what real CLI tools like Terraform do.\n\nLooking at the example workflow, I'm considering how to best visualize the branching paths and reconnections...\n\nBuilding the ASCII diagram with boxes for each step, arrows showing transitions, and branch labels for different outcomes... I'm thinking through how to render this workflow graph programmatically—the ASCII-art approach with boxes and connecting lines is clean and handles arbitrary topologies well. I need to topologically sort the steps first, then draw each node as a box with its connections shown below, which will let me handle merging paths and apply styling to the wire lines.\n\nFor the color scheme, I'll use green for success paths, red for failures, and cycle through other colors for additional result types. Terminal nodes like DONE and ABORT get their own styling too. I should also mark the entry point with a visual indicator so it's clear where the workflow starts.\n\nImplementing the graph rendering now...\n\nFor ordering the steps, I'll do a breadth-first traversal starting from the entry point, which naturally handles cycles by skipping already-visited steps rather than getting stuck in loops.\n\nWriting the command handler... Writing the workflow graph renderer...\n\nNow I'm working on the step box rendering, deciding whether to place the type label inside or outside the box—outside seems cleaner and keeps the box width consistent for the step name itself.\n\nFor the wire rendering, I need to group outgoing wires by their destination step and handle the merging logic properly.\n\nImplementing wire grouping... Setting up color mappings for the results, with green and red for the standard outcomes and a cycle of blue, yellow, orange, and magenta for any other paths that come up. Now I need to figure out how to apply these colors when rendering the wire labels.\n\nI'm thinking the cleanest approach is to color each result word individually while keeping the structural characters like branch connectors and arrows in their default color—that way the output stays readable and the color coding is precise. For merged wires with multiple result types, I'll just color each result word according to its own type.\n\nNow I need to handle the `--project` flag by resolving relative paths to absolute ones, and I should add error handling for missing directories, no workflow files found, invalid workflow names, and parsing failures. I'm also planning out the test cases I'll need: workflow listing, graph rendering, wire merging, BFS ordering, and error scenarios.\n\nImplementing this now...\n\nI'll need to think through how `ParseForContainer` works versus `ParseAllForHost` since one handles a single workflow and the other handles multiples. For listing mode, I'll discover all workflow files, parse them, and group by type. I should also make sure the graph rendering handles collect nodes if they exist, and for the BFS ordering, I'll skip already-visited nodes to handle cycles like the `fix -> test` pattern in the develop workflow.\n\nStill implementing the parser functions... The parser sets the location via `WithLocation`, not the workflow file itself, so the convention is straightforward: `host.cloche` uses `ParseAllForHost` for multiple workflows, while other `.cloche` files use `ParseForContainer` for single workflows. My discovery logic will glob all `.cloche/*.cloche` files and route them accordingly. Before I start writing, I need to check how the parser handles `file(...)` syntax in prompts to understand what gets passed to the rendering layer.\n\nActually, I realize I don't need to dig into that—the parser already handles it, and I'm only extracting the workflow structure for rendering anyway, not processing the prompt content itself. If there's a parse error, I'll surface it to the user. Let me start writing the code.\n\nI'm planning out the structure: a main command handler, a function to discover and parse workflows from the project, separate functions for list and graph display modes, a graph renderer that works with the domain model, a BFS ordering function for topological sorting, and a helper for coloring wire results. I'll also need tests for the rendering and ordering logic.\n\nWriting the Go implementation... Parsing command-line arguments to extract the project directory and workflow name, then defaulting to the current working directory if no project is specified. If no workflow name is given, I'll list all available workflows; otherwise, I'll display the specific one requested. Now I'm setting up a function to discover workflows by scanning the `.cloche` directory for workflow files and reading their metadata.\n\nReading workflow files and parsing them based on their type—host workflows get parsed differently than container workflows—then collecting all discovered workflows into a structured list to return.\n\nNow I'm handling the results by checking for errors, and if workflows were found, I'm separating them into container and host categories, sorting each group alphabetically, and printing them out in organized sections. Writing the workflow display logic... Building the rendering function... Writing the step box rendering... Writing the wire rendering logic... Writing the BFS traversal...\n\nActually, I need to be careful about determinism here—the `bfsOrder` function iterates over `w.Wiring` which is a slice so the order is stable, and I'm using a `seen` map to avoid duplicates within each step's neighbors. The `dest` naming for non-terminal steps is straightforward since I'm just using the step name itself.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the color assignment strategy. The spec is clear: \"success\" should always be green, \"fail\" or \"failed\" should always be red, and other result names get assigned from a palette of blue, yellow, orange, and magenta. I need to build a consistent mapping where the same result name gets the same color everywhere in the workflow, so I'm creating a function that pre-assigns colors to result names based on these rules.\n\nBuilding the result color map... Writing the rendering function...\n\nNow I'm thinking through the test strategy—I'll need to verify the breadth-first ordering, wire grouping logic, and the full rendering pipeline, plus test edge cases like empty workflows, single steps, cycles, and multiple wires converging to the same destination.\n\nFor collects, I realize they're a special case that combines multiple inputs, but since the example workflows don't use them, I'll keep the implementation simple for now and focus on regular step wiring. I should also make sure to handle cases where a destination references a step that isn't defined elsewhere in the workflow.\n\nNow I'm finalizing the code with a few key priorities: ensuring colors only display when stdout is a TTY, using proper box drawing characters for clean rendering, marking the entry step clearly, merging wires that point to the same destination like DONE or ABORT, and keeping the output deterministic through sorting. I also need to handle relative paths for the project directory by converting them to absolute paths.\n\nI'm realizing the test file will need updating too—if I add \"workflow\" to the subcommand help, I'll need to add it to the test's command list as well.\n\nNow I'm thinking about the top-level help text and how to present the workflow command alongside the other sections. Let me refine the ASCII graph rendering to make it feel more like an actual graph visualization rather than just a simple tree structure.\n\nI'm reconsidering whether my current box-and-branch design captures the \"graph\" aesthetic the user wants. The tree-branch approach with connecting lines does show the flow between nodes effectively, similar to how git visualizes commit history. I think this style works well for displaying complex workflows clearly.\n\nI should also make sure to handle cases where steps connect through collect operations, not just direct wires, so the visualization covers all possible connection types.\n\nNow I'm ready to start implementing the code...\n\nActually, let me verify the exact output format one more time by checking what the develop workflow should look like with my box-and-branch style.\n\nWriting the visualization code... That looks clean and readable. The colors would make it pop in a terminal. Wire merging is working for \"fail, give-up -> ABORT\" and \"success, fail -> DONE\".\n\nNow I need to ensure all boxes in a workflow have the same width for visual consistency. I'll compute the maximum step name length and use that to center each step name within its box.\n\nWriting the box rendering code... I'm refining the renderStepBox function to properly pad step names based on the maximum