{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_018aamyWRM2goRrzki6C1djm","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The test `TestRenderWorkflowGraph_DevelopWorkflow` is failing. The issue is that the BFS order places fix before update-docs (since fix is reachable from test, which is before update-docs). But the test's string index check is fragile because \"fix\" appears in the step box line as `│ fix` but also in the wire text from test (\"──▶ fix\"). The test was checking `│ fix` to find the step box for fix, but it actually also matches wire references.\n\nLet me look at the issue more carefully. The positions are:\n- impl=86\n\n\n- test=290\n- fix=661\n- docs=397\n\nThe BFS order should be: implement -> test -> (fix and update-docs). Since test has wires to both update-docs and fix, whichever appears first in the wiring determines the order. The wiring shows update-docs comes before fix, so update-docs should appear first in BFS. But the test checks `fixIdx < docsIdx`, which would fail since fix appears after update-docs in the output.\n\nThe test assertion is checking for impl < test < fix < docs, but the actual BFS order from the wiring is impl < test < docs < fix. The test expectations are backwards—I need to fix the assertion to match what BFS actually produces based on the wiring order. I see the issue now—the test is checking `fixIdx >= docsIdx`, which passes at 661 >= 397, but that's actually validating the wrong order. The correct BFS sequence should be implement, test, update-docs, then fix, so I need to flip the assertion to ensure docs comes before fix. I'll also switch to matching the box format `\"│ fix\"` instead of just `\"fix\"` to avoid picking up references in the wire connections.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3347,"cache_read_input_tokens":75580,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1